<paragraph blockId="8.[155,793,698,1956]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">
Distribution. India to SE Asia, also found in Madagascar and Mauritius; degraded scrubland and secondary vegetation, 
<quantity metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.5" metricValueMax="5.0" metricValueMin="0.0" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" unit="m" value="250.0" valueMax="500.0" valueMin="0.0">0– 500 m</quantity>
elevation.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="8" pageNumber="9" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="8.[155,793,698,1956]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">
Our circumscription of 
<taxonomicName box="[425,524,782,804]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="insanum">
<emphasis box="[425,524,782,804]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">S. insanum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
comprises ‘‘ 
<taxonomicName box="[655,793,783,805]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="melongena">S. melongena</taxonomicName>
group E’’ and ‘‘ 
<taxonomicName box="[307,439,811,833]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="melongena">S. melongena</taxonomicName>
group F’’ of Daunay et al. [
<bibRefCitation author="Daunay M-C &amp; Lester RN &amp; Ano G" box="[712,741,811,833]" editor="Charrier A &amp; Jacquot A &amp; Hamon M &amp; Nicolas D" journalOrPublisher="Montpellier: Science Publishers" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" pagination="199 - 222" refId="ref10704" refString="23. Daunay M-C, Lester RN, Ano G (2001) Eggplant. In: Charrier A, Jacquot A, Hamon M, Nicolas D, editors. Tropical plant breeding. Montpellier: Science Publishers, 199 - 222." title="Eggplant" type="book chapter" volumeTitle="Tropical plant breeding" year="2001">23</bibRefCitation>
]; this includes those plants considered by them to represent wild progenitors and straggling prostrate forms they considered to be feral ‘‘reversions’’ from cultivated forms. This variation in habit is found in some other species of 
<taxonomicName box="[450,521,923,945]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[450,521,923,945]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Solanum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
such as 
<taxonomicName authority="Peralta" authorityName="Peralta" box="[602,771,923,945]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="arcanum">
<emphasis box="[602,695,923,945]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">S. arcanum</emphasis>
Peralta
</taxonomicName>
, a wild tomato from northern Peru [
<bibRefCitation author="Spooner DM &amp; Peralta IE &amp; Knapp S" box="[478,507,951,973]" journalOrPublisher="Taxon" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" pagination="43 - 61" part="54" refId="ref11625" refString="48. Spooner DM, Peralta IE, Knapp S (2005) Comparison of AFLPs with other markers for phylogenetic inference in wild tomatoes [Solanum L. section Lycopersicon (Mill.) Wettst.]. Taxon 54: 43 - 61." title="Comparison of AFLPs with other markers for phylogenetic inference in wild tomatoes [Solanum L. section Lycopersicon (Mill.) Wettst.]" type="journal article" year="2005">48</bibRefCitation>
]. Populations of 
<taxonomicName box="[667,760,951,973]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="insanum">
<emphasis box="[667,760,951,973]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">S. insanum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
we have seen in southern China often have a mixture of forms; prostrate forms appear to grow in more open areas. Common garden experiments coupled with inter-lifeform crosses are necessary to determine the basis of this habit difference.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="8.[155,793,698,1956]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">
<taxonomicName box="[179,329,1092,1114]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="insanum">
<emphasis box="[179,329,1092,1114]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Solanum insanum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is almost certainly the wild progenitor of the cultivated eggplant and is fully interfertile with it [
<bibRefCitation author="Daunay M-C &amp; Hazra P" box="[630,658,1120,1142]" editor="Peter KV &amp; Hazra P" journalOrPublisher="Houston: Studium Press" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" pagination="257 - 322" refId="ref10579" refString="19. Daunay M-C, Hazra P (2012) Eggplant. In: Peter KV, Hazra P, editors. Handbook of Vegetables. Houston: Studium Press, 257 - 322." title="Eggplant" type="book chapter" volumeTitle="Handbook of Vegetables" year="2012">19</bibRefCitation>
]. Meyer et al. [
<bibRefCitation author="Meyer RS &amp; Karol KG &amp; Little DP &amp; Nee MH &amp; Litt A" box="[161,188,1149,1171]" journalOrPublisher="Mol Phylogenet Evol" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" pagination="685 - 701" part="63" refId="ref10639" refString="21. Meyer RS, Karol KG, Little DP, Nee MH, Litt A (2012) Phylogeographic relationships among Asian eggplants and new perspectives on eggplant domestication. Mol Phylogenet Evol 63: 685 - 701." title="Phylogeographic relationships among Asian eggplants and new perspectives on eggplant domestication" type="journal article" year="2012">21</bibRefCitation>
] used AFLPs to test the relationships of wild and cultivated landrace eggplants and suggested that all Asian plants they analysed represented a single species (their 
<taxonomicName box="[655,762,1204,1226]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="incanum">
<emphasis box="[655,762,1204,1226]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">S. incanum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
+ 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="undatum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">S. undatum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
= our 
<taxonomicName box="[296,394,1232,1254]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="insanum">
<emphasis box="[296,394,1232,1254]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">S. insanum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) that was possibly of hybrid origin or had crossed repeatedly with local landraces of 
<taxonomicName box="[670,787,1260,1282]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="melongena">
<emphasis box="[670,787,1260,1282]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">S. melongena</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Regardless of which of these two scenarios is the case, 
<taxonomicName box="[685,792,1288,1310]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="melongena">
<emphasis box="[685,792,1288,1310]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">S. melongena</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is likely to have had its origin(s) from amongst populations of Asian 
<taxonomicName box="[155,247,1344,1366]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="insanum">
<emphasis box="[155,247,1344,1366]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">S. insanum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, as Meyer et al. [
<bibRefCitation author="Meyer RS &amp; Karol KG &amp; Little DP &amp; Nee MH &amp; Litt A" box="[414,441,1345,1367]" journalOrPublisher="Mol Phylogenet Evol" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" pagination="685 - 701" part="63" refId="ref10639" refString="21. Meyer RS, Karol KG, Little DP, Nee MH, Litt A (2012) Phylogeographic relationships among Asian eggplants and new perspectives on eggplant domestication. Mol Phylogenet Evol 63: 685 - 701." title="Phylogeographic relationships among Asian eggplants and new perspectives on eggplant domestication" type="journal article" year="2012">21</bibRefCitation>
] pointed out. 
<taxonomicName box="[577,723,1344,1366]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="insanum">
<emphasis box="[577,723,1344,1366]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Solanum insanum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is used medicinally in south China and is considered distinct from the cultivated 
<taxonomicName box="[261,374,1401,1423]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="melongena">
<emphasis box="[261,374,1401,1423]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">S. melongena</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by local people (pers. obs.). Because 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="insanum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">S. insanum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and cultivated 
<taxonomicName box="[396,510,1429,1450]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="melongena">
<emphasis box="[396,510,1429,1450]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">S. melongena</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are highly interfertile and repeated introgression occurred and is still occurring between wild and cultivated plants individual plants can sometimes be difficult to assign to species unambiguously. In this case we have adapted the method used by Peralta et al. [
<bibRefCitation author="Peralta IE &amp; Spooner DM &amp; Knapp S" box="[493,507,1541,1563]" journalOrPublisher="Syst Bot Monogr" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" pagination="1 - 186" part="84" refId="ref10168" refString="8. Peralta IE, Spooner DM, Knapp S (2008) Taxonomy of wild tomatoes and their relatives (Solanum sections Lycopersicoides, Juglandifolia, Lycopersicon; Solanaceae). Syst Bot Monogr 84: 1 - 186." title="Taxonomy of wild tomatoes and their relatives (Solanum sections Lycopersicoides, Juglandifolia, Lycopersicon; Solanaceae)" type="journal article" year="2008">8</bibRefCitation>
] for naming plants that were morphologically intermediate between the cultivated tomato (
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="lycopersicum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">S. lycopersicum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) and its wild progenitor (
<taxonomicName box="[503,660,1597,1618]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="pimpinellifolium">
<emphasis box="[503,660,1597,1618]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">S. pimpinellifolium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
L.). They [
<bibRefCitation author="Peralta IE &amp; Spooner DM &amp; Knapp S" box="[771,785,1597,1619]" journalOrPublisher="Syst Bot Monogr" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" pagination="1 - 186" part="84" refId="ref10168" refString="8. Peralta IE, Spooner DM, Knapp S (2008) Taxonomy of wild tomatoes and their relatives (Solanum sections Lycopersicoides, Juglandifolia, Lycopersicon; Solanaceae). Syst Bot Monogr 84: 1 - 186." title="Taxonomy of wild tomatoes and their relatives (Solanum sections Lycopersicoides, Juglandifolia, Lycopersicon; Solanaceae)" type="journal article" year="2008">8</bibRefCitation>
] defined a suite of characters that distinguish each species and an individual specimen having a majority of one set of these is called that species. 
<tableCitation box="[280,356,1682,1704]" captionStart="Table 3" captionStartId="6.[171,235,174,195]" captionTargetBox="[171,1387,258,515]" captionTargetId="graphics-946@6.[171,1478,355,388]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Table 3. Character suite for distinguishing ambiguous specimens of S. insanum and S. melongena." httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/DF567DD0FFC8FFD2FF25FF05FB2E1CA1" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" tableUuid="DF567DD0FFC8FFD2FF25FF05FB2E1CA1">Table 3</tableCitation>
lists the suite of characters we have used for the eggplants; for example, a specimen with several long-styled, 5- merous flowers (
<figureCitation box="[317,391,1738,1760]" captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="4.[155,220,172,191]" captionTargetBox="[160,1391,167,1911]" captionTargetId="figure-0@3.[155,1397,162,1916]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figure 1. Representative flower and fruit morphology of eggplant and its wild relatives. A. Solanum campylacanthum inflorescences (Kenya - Vorontsova et al. 157); B. Solanum incanum immature fruit (Kenya – Vorontsova et al. 203); C. Solanum insanum fruit cross-section (China – Wang et al. 2047); D. Solanum insanum inflorescence with several hermaphrodite flowers (China – Wang et al. 2039); E. Solanum linnaeanum with yellow mature and mottled green immature fruit, note highly dissected leaves (Spain - Knapp IM-10096); F. Solanum melongena flower with duplicated parts (China – Wang et al. 2042). Photographs: A, B taken M.S. Vorontsova; C, D, E, F taken by S. Knapp. doi:10.1371/journal.pone.0057039.g001" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6338574" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6338574/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Fig. 1D</figureCitation>
), non-prickly stems and juicy green fruit pulp (
<figureCitation box="[213,284,1766,1788]" captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="4.[155,220,172,191]" captionTargetBox="[160,1391,167,1911]" captionTargetId="figure-0@3.[155,1397,162,1916]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figure 1. Representative flower and fruit morphology of eggplant and its wild relatives. A. Solanum campylacanthum inflorescences (Kenya - Vorontsova et al. 157); B. Solanum incanum immature fruit (Kenya – Vorontsova et al. 203); C. Solanum insanum fruit cross-section (China – Wang et al. 2047); D. Solanum insanum inflorescence with several hermaphrodite flowers (China – Wang et al. 2039); E. Solanum linnaeanum with yellow mature and mottled green immature fruit, note highly dissected leaves (Spain - Knapp IM-10096); F. Solanum melongena flower with duplicated parts (China – Wang et al. 2042). Photographs: A, B taken M.S. Vorontsova; C, D, E, F taken by S. Knapp. doi:10.1371/journal.pone.0057039.g001" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6338574" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6338574/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Fig. 1C</figureCitation>
) would be called 
<taxonomicName box="[464,559,1766,1787]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="insanum">
<emphasis box="[464,559,1766,1787]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">S. insanum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, while a specimen with prickly stems, rounded leaf lobes, one long-styled fascinated flower (
<figureCitation box="[161,226,1822,1844]" captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="4.[155,220,172,191]" captionTargetBox="[160,1391,167,1911]" captionTargetId="figure-0@3.[155,1397,162,1916]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figure 1. Representative flower and fruit morphology of eggplant and its wild relatives. A. Solanum campylacanthum inflorescences (Kenya - Vorontsova et al. 157); B. Solanum incanum immature fruit (Kenya – Vorontsova et al. 203); C. Solanum insanum fruit cross-section (China – Wang et al. 2047); D. Solanum insanum inflorescence with several hermaphrodite flowers (China – Wang et al. 2039); E. Solanum linnaeanum with yellow mature and mottled green immature fruit, note highly dissected leaves (Spain - Knapp IM-10096); F. Solanum melongena flower with duplicated parts (China – Wang et al. 2042). Photographs: A, B taken M.S. Vorontsova; C, D, E, F taken by S. Knapp. doi:10.1371/journal.pone.0057039.g001" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6338574" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6338574/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Fig. 1F</figureCitation>
) and large fruit would be called 
<taxonomicName box="[539,646,1821,1843]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="melongena">
<emphasis box="[539,646,1821,1843]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">S. melongena</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Fruit colour is not a particularly reliable character, as it changes through fruit development (see 
<figureCitation box="[329,400,1878,1900]" captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="4.[155,220,172,191]" captionTargetBox="[160,1391,167,1911]" captionTargetId="figure-0@3.[155,1397,162,1916]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figure 1. Representative flower and fruit morphology of eggplant and its wild relatives. A. Solanum campylacanthum inflorescences (Kenya - Vorontsova et al. 157); B. Solanum incanum immature fruit (Kenya – Vorontsova et al. 203); C. Solanum insanum fruit cross-section (China – Wang et al. 2047); D. Solanum insanum inflorescence with several hermaphrodite flowers (China – Wang et al. 2039); E. Solanum linnaeanum with yellow mature and mottled green immature fruit, note highly dissected leaves (Spain - Knapp IM-10096); F. Solanum melongena flower with duplicated parts (China – Wang et al. 2042). Photographs: A, B taken M.S. Vorontsova; C, D, E, F taken by S. Knapp. doi:10.1371/journal.pone.0057039.g001" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6338574" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6338574/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Fig. 1E</figureCitation>
); 
<taxonomicName box="[420,528,1877,1899]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="melongena">
<emphasis box="[420,528,1877,1899]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">S. melongena</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
fruits are eaten when they are unripe, so the various green and purple fruits eventually become yellow or brownish yellow if left to ripen completely.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="8.[840,1478,164,410]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">
Hepper and Jaeger [
<bibRefCitation author="Hepper FN &amp; Jaeger P-ML" box="[1098,1126,164,186]" journalOrPublisher="Kew Bull" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" pagination="387 - 391" part="40" refId="ref11482" refString="45. Hepper FN, Jaeger P-ML (1985) The typification of six Linnaean names in Solanum. Kew Bull 40: 387 - 391." title="The typification of six Linnaean names in Solanum" type="journal article" year="1985">45</bibRefCitation>
] clearly describe how Linnaeus described 
<taxonomicName box="[943,1040,192,214]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="insanum">
<emphasis box="[943,1040,192,214]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">S. insanum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as distinct from his earlier 
<taxonomicName box="[1332,1443,192,214]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="melongena">
<emphasis box="[1332,1443,192,214]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">S. melongena</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by citing its prickly stems (in addition to calyx) thus indicating he considered 
<taxonomicName box="[952,1046,247,269]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="insanum">
<emphasis box="[952,1046,247,269]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">S. insanum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
a new species and not a replacement name for 
<taxonomicName box="[875,982,275,297]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="melongena">
<emphasis box="[875,982,275,297]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">S. melongena</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as 
<taxonomicName box="[1015,1106,275,297]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="sanctum">
<emphasis box="[1015,1106,275,297]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">S. sanctum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was for 
<taxonomicName box="[1190,1283,275,297]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="incanum">
<emphasis box="[1190,1283,275,297]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">S. incanum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in [
<bibRefCitation author="Linnaeus C" box="[1323,1353,276,298]" journalOrPublisher="Stockholm: Salvius" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" refId="ref11671" refString="49. Linnaeus C (1759) Systema naturae (2 vols.). Stockholm: Salvius." title="Systema naturae (2 vols.)" type="book" year="1759">49</bibRefCitation>
]. It has been suggested that 
<taxonomicName box="[989,1085,303,325]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="insanum">
<emphasis box="[989,1085,303,325]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">S. insanum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was a misprint for 
<taxonomicName box="[1289,1385,303,325]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="incanum">
<emphasis box="[1289,1385,303,325]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">S. incanum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
[
<bibRefCitation author="Hepper FN &amp; Jaeger P-ML" box="[1402,1430,304,326]" journalOrPublisher="Kew Bull" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" pagination="387 - 391" part="40" refId="ref11482" refString="45. Hepper FN, Jaeger P-ML (1985) The typification of six Linnaean names in Solanum. Kew Bull 40: 387 - 391." title="The typification of six Linnaean names in Solanum" type="journal article" year="1985">45</bibRefCitation>
] but although it is unfortunate the two names are very similar they are not considered confusable (R. Brummitt, pers. comm.). Meyer et al. [
<bibRefCitation author="Meyer RS &amp; Karol KG &amp; Little DP &amp; Nee MH &amp; Litt A" box="[903,930,388,410]" journalOrPublisher="Mol Phylogenet Evol" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" pagination="685 - 701" part="63" refId="ref10639" refString="21. Meyer RS, Karol KG, Little DP, Nee MH, Litt A (2012) Phylogeographic relationships among Asian eggplants and new perspectives on eggplant domestication. Mol Phylogenet Evol 63: 685 - 701." title="Phylogeographic relationships among Asian eggplants and new perspectives on eggplant domestication" type="journal article" year="2012">21</bibRefCitation>
] erroneously considered 
<taxonomicName box="[1176,1270,387,409]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="insanum">
<emphasis box="[1176,1270,387,409]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">S. insanum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as illegitimate.
</paragraph>
